04221nam a22005655i 9780226510316DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265103167 a10.7208/97802265103162doi  a(DE-B1597)522572  a(OCoLC)1015676254  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJK1083 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a328.7309221 aBernhard, William, eauthor.10aLegislative Style /cTracy Sulkin, William Bernhard. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b36 line drawings, 26 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Legislative Style and Congressional Careers -- tChapter Two. Measuring Legislative Style / rSewell, Daniel -- tChapter Three. The Styles -- tChapter Four. Explaining Freshman Styles -- tChapter Five. Transitions in Style -- tChapter Six. The Electoral Consequences of Legislative Style -- tChapter Seven. Styles, Lawmaking, and Legislative Success -- tChapter Eight. Career Advancement and Legislative Styles -- tChapter Nine. Legislative Styles and Evaluations of Congress -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tChicago Studies in American Politics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOnce elected, members of Congress face difficult decisions about how to allocate their time and effort. On which issues should they focus? What is the right balance between working in one's district and on Capitol Hill? How much should they engage with the media to cultivate a national reputation? William Bernhard and Tracy Sulkin argue that these decisions and others define a "legislative style" that aligns with a legislator's ambitions, experiences, and personal inclinations, as well as any significant electoral and institutional constraints. Bernhard and Sulkin have developed a systematic approach for looking at legislative style through a variety of criteria, including the number of the bills passed, number of speeches given, amount of money raised, and the percentage of time a legislator voted in line with his or her party. Applying this to ten congresses, representing twenty years of congressional data, from 1989 to 2009, they reveal that legislators' activity falls within five predictable styles. These styles remain relatively consistent throughout legislators' time in office, though a legislator's style can change as career goals evolve, as well as with changes to individual or larger political interests, as in redistricting or a majority shift. Offering insight into a number of enduring questions in legislative politics, Legislative Style is a rich and nuanced account of legislators' activity on Capitol Hill.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aLegislationzUnited StatesxDecision making. 0aLegislatorszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aPolitical planningzUnited States. 4aCongress. 4alegislative activity. 4alegislative careers. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aSulkin, Tracy, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226510316423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226510316.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles